#### Image 7  

Fallout (also known as Fallout: A Post Nuclear Role Playing Game ) is a 1997 [role‑playing video game](/Role-playing_video_game) developed and published by [Interplay Productions](/Interplay_Productions), set in a mid‑22nd century [post‑apocalyptic](/Post-apocalyptic) and [retro‑futuristic](/Retro-futuristic) world, decades after a global [nuclear war](/Nuclear_war) led by the United States and China. Fallout ’s protagonist, the Vault Dweller, inhabits an underground nuclear shelter. The player must scour the surrounding wasteland for a computer chip that can fix the Vault's failed water supply system. They interact with other survivors, some of whom give them [quests](/Quest_(video_games)), and engage in [turn‑based](/Turn-based) combat.  

[Tim Cain](/Tim_Cain) began working on Fallout in 1994. It began and was conceptualized as based on the role‑playing game [GURPS](/GURPS), but after [Steve Jackson Games](/Steve_Jackson_Games) objected to Fallout ’s violence, Cain and designer [Christopher Taylor](/Christopher_Taylor_(game_designer)) created a new character customization scheme, SPECIAL. Interplay initially gave the game little attention, but eventually spent $3 million and employed up to thirty people to develop it. Interplay considered Fallout the spiritual successor to its 1988 role‑playing game [Wasteland](/Wasteland_(video_game)) and drew artistic inspiration from 1950s literature and media emblematic of the [Atomic Age](/Atomic_Age) as well as the films [Mad Max](/Mad_Max) and [A Boy and His Dog](/A_Boy_and_His_Dog_(1975_film)) . The quests were intentionally made [morally ambiguous](/Moral_ambiguity). After three and a half years of development, Fallout was released in North America in October 1997.  

Fallout received acclaim for its open‑ended gameplay, character system, plot, and setting. It won "Role‑Playing Game of the Year" from [GameSpot](/GameSpot) and [Computer Games Magazine](/Computer_Games_Magazine) and was nominated by the [Academy of Interactive Arts & Sciences](/Academy_of_Interactive_Arts_%26_Sciences) at the [Spotlight Awards](/Spotlight_Awards). Fallout was a commercial success, selling more than half a million copies worldwide. Often listed among the [greatest video games of all time](/Greatest_video_games_of_all_time), Fallout has been credited for renewing consumer interest in the role‑playing video game genre. It spawned the widely successful Fallout series , the rights to which were purchased in 2007 by [Bethesda Softworks](/Bethesda_Softworks). ( [Full article...](/Fallout_(video_game)) )  

