#### Image 8  

[Maniac Mansion](/Maniac_Mansion) is a 1987 [graphic adventure](/Graphic_adventure_game) video game developed and published by [Lucasfilm Games](/Lucasfilm_Games). It follows teenage protagonist Dave Miller as he attempts to rescue his girlfriend Sandy Pantz from a [mad scientist](/Mad_scientist), whose mind has been enslaved by a sentient meteor. The player uses a [point‑and‑click](/Point-and-click) interface to guide Dave and two of his six playable friends through the scientist's mansion while solving puzzles and avoiding dangers. Gameplay is [non‑linear](/Nonlinear_gameplay), and the game must be completed in different ways based on the player's choice of characters. Initially released for the [Commodore 64](/Commodore_64) and [Apple II](/Apple_II), Maniac Mansion was Lucasfilm Games' first [self‑published](/Self-publishing) product.  

The game was conceived in 1985 by [Ron Gilbert](/Ron_Gilbert) and [Gary Winnick](/Gary_Winnick_(game_developer)), who sought to tell a comedic story based on horror film and [B‑movie](/B-movie) clichés. They mapped out the project as a [paper‑and‑pencil game](/Paper-and-pencil_game) before coding commenced. While earlier adventure titles had relied on [command lines](/Command-line_interface), Gilbert disliked such systems, and he developed Maniac Mansion ’s simpler point‑and‑click interface as a replacement. To speed up production, he created a [game engine](/Game_engine) called [SCUMM](/SCUMM), which was used in [many later LucasArts titles](/LucasArts_adventure_games). After its release, Maniac Mansion was [ported](/Porting_of_video_games) to several platforms. A port for the [Nintendo Entertainment System](/Nintendo_Entertainment_System) had to be reworked heavily, in response to [Nintendo of America](/Nintendo_of_America)'s concerns that the game was inappropriate for children.  

Maniac Mansion was critically acclaimed: reviewers lauded its graphics, [cutscenes](/Cutscene), animation, and humor. Writer [Orson Scott Card](/Orson_Scott_Card) praised it as a step toward "computer games [becoming] a valid storytelling art". It influenced numerous graphic adventure titles, and its point‑and‑click interface became a standard feature in the genre. The game's success solidified Lucasfilm as a serious rival to adventure game studios such as [Sierra On‑Line](/Sierra_Entertainment). In 1990, Maniac Mansion was adapted into a three‑season [television series of the same name](/Maniac_Mansion_(TV_series)), written by [Eugene Levy](/Eugene_Levy) and starring [Joe Flaherty](/Joe_Flaherty). A sequel to the game, [Day of the Tentacle](/Day_of_the_Tentacle) , was released in 1993. ( [Full article...](/Maniac_Mansion) )  

