#### Image 10  

Aquaria is a [side‑scrolling](/Side-scrolling_video_game) [action‑adventure game](/Action-adventure_game) designed by [Alec Holowka](/Alec_Holowka) and [Derek Yu](/Derek_Yu), who [published](/Video_game_publisher) the game in 2007 as an [independent game company](/Indie_game_development) Bit Blot. The game follows Naija, an aquatic [humanoid](/Humanoid) woman, as she explores the underwater world of Aquaria. Along her journey, she learns about the history of the world she inhabits as well as her own past. The [gameplay](/Gameplay) focuses on a combination of swimming, singing, and combat, through which Naija can interact with the world. Her songs can move items, affect plants and animals, and change her physical appearance into other forms that have different abilities, like firing projectiles at hostile creatures, or passing through barriers inaccessible to her in her natural form.  

After more than two years of development, the game was released in late 2007 for [Windows](/Microsoft_Windows). A [port](/Porting) of the game to [Mac OS X](/Mac_OS_X) was released in 2008 by [Ambrosia Software](/Ambrosia_Software), and an updated version of the game was released on the [Steam](/Steam_(service)) service that same year. A [Linux](/Linux) version of the game was released as part of the first [Humble Indie Bundle](/Humble_Bundle) collection in 2010, a version for the [iPad](/IPad) was released in 2011, and an [Android](/Android_(operating_system)) version debuted in 2013 alongside another Humble Bundle collection. In 2009, an album with the Aquaria soundtrack was released. It includes all of the music in the game, as well as a new nine‑minute vocal track and a few remixes.  

Reviews of the game were generally positive. Critics focused primarily on the visuals, music, and atmosphere as being particularly praiseworthy. The controls and gameplay were also lauded, while negative critiques more often centered on the map system and limited variety of [objectives](/Glossary_of_video_game_terms). The game won the [Seumas McNally Grand Prize](/Seumas_McNally_Grand_Prize) at the [Independent Games Festival](/Independent_Games_Festival) in March 2007. ( [Full article...](/Aquaria_(video_game)) )  

