**Image 1** – Mechner in 2017  

[Jordan Mechner](/Jordan_Mechner) (born June 4, 1964) is an American [video‑game designer](/Video_game_designer), [graphic novelist](/Graphic_novelist), author, [screenwriter](/Screenwriter), filmmaker, and former video‑game programmer. A major figure in the development of cinematic video games and a pioneer in video‑game animation, he began his career designing and programming the bestselling 1984 martial‑arts game [Karateka](/Karateka_(video_game)) for the [Apple II](/Apple_II) while a student at [Yale University](/Yale_University). He followed it with the platform game [Prince of Persia](/Prince_of_Persia_(1989_video_game)) five years later; it was widely ported and became a hit. Both games used [rotoscoping](/Rotoscoping), where actors shot on film by Mechner were drawn over to create in‑game animation. Prince of Persia has become the basis for a long‑running franchise, including a [2010 live‑action film](/Prince_of_Persia:_The_Sands_of_Time_(film)) released by Walt Disney Pictures and an ongoing [series of video games](/Prince_of_Persia) published by Ubisoft.  

Mechner is the recipient of many accolades, including the 2017 [GDC Pioneer Award](/Game_Developers_Choice_Awards). His works are often included in all‑time lists of the game industry's best and most influential titles. ( [Full article...](/Jordan_Mechner) )  

