**Image 6** – Suzuki at the 2011 Game Developers Conference  

[Yu Suzuki](/Yu_Suzuki) (鈴木 裕, Suzuki Yū ; born June 10, 1958) is a Japanese [game designer](/Game_designer), [producer](/Game_producer), [programmer](/Game_programmer), and [engineer](/Engineer), who headed [Sega](/Sega)'s [AM2](/Sega_AM2) team for 18 years. Considered one of the first [auteurs](/Auteurs) of video games, he has been responsible for a number of Sega's [arcade](/Arcade_game) hits, including [three‑dimensional](/2.5D) [sprite](/Sprite_(computer_graphics))‑scaling games that used "taikan" [motion simulator](/Motion_simulator) [arcade cabinets](/Arcade_cabinet), such as [Hang‑On](/Hang-On) , [Space Harrier](/Space_Harrier) , [Out Run](/Out_Run) and [After Burner](/After_Burner) , and pioneering [polygonal 3D](/3D_computer_graphics) games such as [Virtua Racing](/Virtua_Racing) and [Virtua Fighter](/Virtua_Fighter_(series)) , which are some of the games besides others from rival companies during that era credited with popularizing 3D graphics in video games; as well as the critically acclaimed [Shenmue](/Shenmue) series. As a hardware engineer, he led the development of various [arcade system boards](/Arcade_system_board), including the [Sega Space Harrier](/Sega_Space_Harrier), [Model 1](/Sega_Model_1), [Model 2](/Sega_Model_2) and [Model 3](/Sega_Model_3), and was involved in the technical development of the [Dreamcast](/Dreamcast) console and its corresponding [NAOMI](/Sega_NAOMI) arcade hardware.  

In 2003, Suzuki became the sixth person to be inducted into the [Academy of Interactive Arts and Sciences' Hall of Fame](/Academy_of_Interactive_Arts_and_Sciences%27_Hall_of_Fame). [IGN](/IGN) listed him at #9 in their Top 100 Game Creators of All Time list. In 2011, he received the Pioneer Award at the [Game Developers Choice Awards](/Game_Developers_Choice_Awards). ( [Full article...](/Yu_Suzuki) )  

