**Image 14** – Hiroshi Yamauchi  

[Hiroshi Yamauchi](/Hiroshi_Yamauchi) ([Japanese](/Japanese_language): 山内 溥; 7 November 1927&#160;&#8211;&#32;19 September 2013) was the third president of [Nintendo](/Nintendo), serving in the role from 25 April 1949 to 24 May 2002, and principal owner of the [Seattle Mariners](/Seattle_Mariners) from 1992 until his death. Before joining Nintendo, he had strong familial connections; his great‑grandfather, [Fusajiro Yamauchi](/Fusajiro_Yamauchi), founded the company, and was its first president, and his grandfather, [Sekiryo Kaneda](/Sekiryo_Kaneda), was its second president. During his tenure, Nintendo was transformed from a Japanese manufacturer of [hanafuda](/Hanafuda) into a global conglomerate largely focused on manufacturing [video‑game consoles](/Video_game_consoles) and [publishing video games](/Video_game_publisher). On the basis of this success, and his ownership of most of Nintendo's shares, he became considerably wealthy. In 2008, he was [Japan's wealthiest person](/Forbes_list_of_billionaires_(2008)), with an estimated net worth of $7.8 billion. Even in 2013, with this figure having declined to $2.1 billion, he was the 13th richest person in Japan and the 491st [richest in the world](/Forbes_list_of_billionaires_(2012)). ( [Full article...](/Hiroshi_Yamauchi) )  

