**Image 24** – Iwata at GDC 2011  

[Satoru Iwata](/Satoru_Iwata) ([Japanese](/Japanese_language): 岩田 聡; 6 December 1959 – 11 July 2015) was a Japanese businessman, video‑game programmer and producer. Beginning in 2002, he was the fourth president of [Nintendo](/Nintendo), as well as the [chief executive officer](/Chief_executive_officer) (CEO) of Nintendo of America from 2013 until his death in 2015. Iwata was a major contributor in broadening the appeal of video games by focusing on novel and entertaining games rather than top‑of‑the‑line hardware.  

Born in [Sapporo](/Sapporo), Iwata expressed interest in video games from an early age and created his first simple game while in high school. He majored in [computer science](/Computer_science) at the [Tokyo Institute of Technology](/Tokyo_Institute_of_Technology). In 1980, he joined the game developer [HAL Laboratory](/HAL_Laboratory) while attending the university. At HAL, he worked as a programmer and closely collaborated with Nintendo, producing his first commercial game in 1983. Games to which he contributed include [EarthBound](/EarthBound) and many games in the [Kirby](/Kirby_(series)) series. Following a downturn and near‑bankruptcy, Iwata became the president of HAL in 1993 at the insistence of Nintendo president [Hiroshi Yamauchi](/Hiroshi_Yamauchi) and brought financial stability. In the following years, he worked in the development of the [Pokémon](/Pok%C3%A9mon_(video_game_series)) and [Super Smash Bros.](/Super_Smash_Bros.) series. Iwata joined Nintendo as the head of its corporate planning division in 2000. ( [Full article...](/Satoru_Iwata) )  

